{"id":"1502.00020","submitter":"Hans Ohanian","authors":"Hans C. Ohanian","title":"Weyl gauge-vector and complex dilaton scalar for conformal symmetry and\n  its breaking","comments":null,"journal-ref":"General Relativity and Gravitation, March 2016, 48:25","doi":"10.1007/s10714-016-2023-8","report-no":null,"categories":"gr-qc","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Instead of the scalar \"dilaton\" field that is usually adopted to construct\nconformally invariant Lagrangians for gravitation, we here propose a hybrid\nconstruction, involving both a complex dilaton scalar and a Weyl gauge-vector,\nin accord with Weyl's original concept of a non-Riemannian conformal geometry\nwith a transport law for length and time intervals, for which this gauge vector\nis required. Such a hybrid construction permits us to avoid the wrong sign of\nthe dilaton kinetic term (the ghost problem) that afflicts the usual\nconstruction. The introduction of a Weyl gauge-vector and its interaction with\nthe dilaton also has the collateral benefit of providing an explicit mechanism\nfor spontaneous breaking of the conformal symmetry, whereby the dilaton and the\nWeyl gauge-vector acquire masses somewhat smaller than m/sub/P by the\nColeman-Weinberg mechanism. Conformal symmetry breaking is assumed to precede\ninflation, which occurs later by a separate GUT or electroweak symmetry\nbreaking, as in inflationary models based on the Higgs boson.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 30 Jan 2015 21:27:49 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Wed, 20 Jan 2016 17:17:01 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Mon, 7 Mar 2016 16:06:02 GMT"}],"update_date":"2016-03-08"}
